WEBVTT

00:05.560 --> 00:06.480
(ENGINE REVVING)

00:06.520 --> 00:08.440
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLASTS)

00:54.000 --> 00:55.920
(CHEERING)

00:59.400 --> 01:01.320
Hello.

01:02.840 --> 01:04.840
-Hello.
-Hello, everybody.

01:04.880 --> 01:06.480
Hello.

01:06.520 --> 01:08.440
(CHEERING AND WHISTLING)

01:09.520 --> 01:11.440
RICHARD: Hello.

01:13.120 --> 01:15.040
Thank you.

01:15.080 --> 01:17.480
And - thank you -
and coming up

01:17.520 --> 01:20.080
in this never-to-be-forgotten
show...

01:21.680 --> 01:23.360
...Richard operates a bat...

01:26.080 --> 01:28.200
...James sits in a car
humming...

01:28.240 --> 01:32.320
(HUMMING)

01:32.360 --> 01:35.640
...and I park
outside a cathedral.

01:37.640 --> 01:39.560
-(CHEERING)
-Thank you so much.

01:40.640 --> 01:42.040
Exciting stuff.

01:42.080 --> 01:44.560
Now, this is...

01:44.600 --> 01:47.320
this is a bit of
a Ford-based show.

01:47.360 --> 01:50.720
Because we were staggered
to hear the other day,

01:50.760 --> 01:53.040
that they're thinking of
pulling the plug

01:53.080 --> 01:54.760
on the Mondeo.

01:54.800 --> 01:58.040
Now this is enormous news.

01:58.080 --> 02:01.120
In Britain, losing the Mondeo
is a bit like...

02:01.160 --> 02:03.760
Well,
losing the Royal Family.

02:03.800 --> 02:06.520
And if that happens, someone
would make a documentary
about them.

02:06.560 --> 02:08.840
Quite. Which is why
we decided this week

02:08.880 --> 02:11.040
The Grand Tour
should make a documentary

02:11.080 --> 02:17.040
about the passing of Ford's
medium-sized family saloon.

02:17.080 --> 02:19.080
-It's exciting stuff.
-(LAUGHTER)

02:23.840 --> 02:26.840
The Mondeo story
actually begins way back

02:26.880 --> 02:28.880
when the world
was black and white,

02:28.880 --> 02:31.000
with this -

02:31.040 --> 02:32.960
the Ford Cortina.

02:35.240 --> 02:37.680
This is Genesis,
the first chapter

02:37.720 --> 02:40.880
in easily
the most important book

02:40.960 --> 02:43.040
in British motoring history.

02:45.600 --> 02:47.840
It came along in 1962

02:47.880 --> 02:50.760
and apart from
the CND rear lights,

02:50.800 --> 02:52.720
it was nothing special.

02:54.680 --> 02:56.840
It wasn't revolutionary
like the Mini.

02:56.880 --> 02:59.560
It was just
an ordinary family saloon.

03:02.720 --> 03:05.360
Ford therefore decided
that to put it on the map

03:05.400 --> 03:08.160
they'd mount an assault
on the world's racetracks.

03:08.200 --> 03:11.680
Which meant creating
a high-performance version.

03:11.720 --> 03:15.160
The world's first ever
fast Ford.

03:15.200 --> 03:17.880
And this is what
they came up with.

03:22.320 --> 03:24.080
(ROAR OF ENGINE)

03:33.400 --> 03:36.080
Life doesn't get
much better than this.

03:36.120 --> 03:38.040
Cadwell Park, sunny day...

03:39.120 --> 03:40.520
Mark One Lotus Cortina.

03:42.200 --> 03:44.400
This thing is a riot.

03:44.440 --> 03:46.400
(DRONE OF ENGINE)

03:49.200 --> 03:55.160
It had a revolutionary
twin-cam 1.6 litre engine.

03:55.200 --> 03:56.920
(CHUCKLING)
Which sounds like

03:56.960 --> 03:58.760
a murder of mad bees.

03:58.800 --> 04:01.720
(ENGINE REVS)

04:01.760 --> 04:03.760
It revved like hell.

04:03.800 --> 04:07.080
All the way to 8,000 RPM.

04:07.120 --> 04:10.520
And produced 105 horsepower.

04:13.800 --> 04:15.760
Ha-ha, ha-ha!

04:15.800 --> 04:17.880
Oh, wow!

04:20.960 --> 04:24.640
The result was some
spectacular performance.

04:24.680 --> 04:28.240
The road cars
would do 108 mph.

04:28.320 --> 04:32.480
And in race trim
that shot up to 145.

04:34.200 --> 04:36.800
That was the stuff of
spaceships back then.

04:38.000 --> 04:40.040
And best of all...

04:40.080 --> 04:41.920
if you were really on it,

04:42.000 --> 04:44.720
it would lift the front wheel
in the corners.

04:46.120 --> 04:48.080
(TYRES SCREECH)

04:48.120 --> 04:51.920
On the downside
it didn't stop properly...

04:52.000 --> 04:53.920
...and there was
very little grip.

04:55.520 --> 04:58.200
So it was
an over-steer mentalist.

04:59.920 --> 05:03.600
It was also
astonishingly brittle.

05:03.640 --> 05:06.440
Autocar magazine
ran one for a year.

05:06.480 --> 05:07.880
29,000 miles.

05:07.920 --> 05:11.360
And in that time,
it needed six rear axles

05:11.360 --> 05:14.080
and three sets
of rear suspension.

05:14.120 --> 05:17.000
And probably a whole load of
new half-shafts as well,

05:17.040 --> 05:18.800
because they were made
from chocolate.

05:18.880 --> 05:20.480
But it didn't matter.

05:20.520 --> 05:24.480
Because the Lotus Cortina
wasn't designed to
last a lifetime.

05:24.520 --> 05:28.080
It was designed
to last about 40 minutes.

05:28.120 --> 05:31.520
Because that is
how long a race lasted.

05:33.560 --> 05:37.040
Back in the early '60s,
saloon-car racing in Britain

05:37.080 --> 05:40.080
was just about the most
exciting motor sport

05:40.120 --> 05:43.240
the world had ever seen.

05:43.280 --> 05:46.400
The massive American Fords
would roar down the straights

05:46.440 --> 05:49.000
and then in the corners
the army of Minis

05:49.040 --> 05:50.760
would be right back at them.

05:50.800 --> 05:54.760
It was beautiful,
snarling chaos.

05:54.800 --> 05:56.800
(CRASHING)

05:56.840 --> 05:59.960
But when the dust settled,
it was the Lotus Cortina

06:00.000 --> 06:02.760
that was doing the winning.

06:02.800 --> 06:06.720
-It actually won the
Championship in 1964...
-(APPLAUSE)

06:06.760 --> 06:10.000
...and it didn't only shine
on the tracks.

06:10.040 --> 06:15.360
In 1966, it won the RAC
Rally of Britain.

06:15.400 --> 06:19.160
They even drove one
down the bobsleigh run
in the Italian resort

06:19.200 --> 06:23.640
after which the Cortina
had been named.

06:23.680 --> 06:25.960
REPORTER: Here's what the
famed bobsled run looks like

06:26.000 --> 06:30.400
from the driver's seat of
the world-famous Cortina.

06:30.440 --> 06:33.440
JEREMY:
At this point in history,
rationing had only just

06:33.480 --> 06:35.440
given way to
The Rolling Stones.

06:35.480 --> 06:38.120
-(SCREAMING)
-Hemlines were going up

06:38.160 --> 06:41.600
and all kinds of groovy stuff
was going down.

06:41.640 --> 06:43.880
And the glamorous Cortina

06:43.920 --> 06:46.440
caught the mood
of the moment perfectly.

06:48.760 --> 06:52.240
It was exciting.
The first car ever that made

06:52.280 --> 06:55.000
the ordinary family man
feel special.

06:55.040 --> 06:58.440
Like he wasn't just
a downtrodden cog.

06:58.480 --> 07:01.520
And it was the same story
with the Mark II Cortina.

07:01.560 --> 07:04.080
And the Mark III.

07:04.120 --> 07:05.680
(CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKS)

07:05.720 --> 07:07.360
The result was spectacular.

07:07.400 --> 07:11.560
One car in every three
sold in the UK was a Ford.

07:11.600 --> 07:14.080
And one in ten was a Cortina.

07:14.120 --> 07:18.160
Everyone I've spoken to while
I've been preparing this film
has said the same thing.

07:18.200 --> 07:20.600
"Oh, yeah, my dad
used to have one of those."

07:20.640 --> 07:23.920
I mean, on the crew here,
whose dad had a Cortina?

07:23.960 --> 07:25.640
Ha! Look at that.
It's everyone.

07:25.680 --> 07:29.240
Apart from the director,
obviously, who has a
double-barrelled name,

07:29.280 --> 07:31.400
so his dad had a Range Rover.
But anyway...

07:31.440 --> 07:34.280
the point is, these were
the best-selling cars

07:34.320 --> 07:37.400
Britain had ever seen...
by miles.

07:37.440 --> 07:39.080
(ROCK INSTRUMENTAL)

07:39.120 --> 07:41.480
Of course it wasn't all
rampant sexism

07:41.520 --> 07:47.800
and hilarious handling
that Ford used to make
a name for its family saloon.

07:47.840 --> 07:50.280
There was some important
business stuff too.

07:50.320 --> 07:52.720
(TICKING)

07:52.760 --> 07:57.520
Back in late-1960s Britain,
if you earned £3,000 a year

07:57.560 --> 08:01.760
the government would take
41% of it away in tax.

08:01.800 --> 08:04.000
So, to get round this
problem, a lot of companies

08:04.040 --> 08:05.760
paid their staff a bit less,

08:05.800 --> 08:07.240
but then to make up
the difference

08:07.280 --> 08:09.720
they gave them...a car.

08:09.760 --> 08:11.680
And that...

08:11.720 --> 08:13.760
wasn't subject
to any tax at all.

08:16.200 --> 08:18.200
JEREMY:
Ford cottoned on to that.

08:18.240 --> 08:20.800
And came up with
a variety of trim levels

08:20.840 --> 08:23.520
to suit the typical
management structure.

08:25.200 --> 08:27.600
There was a base model
for the sales rep.

08:28.920 --> 08:32.960
And the L
for the sales manager.

08:33.000 --> 08:36.960
Then you had the XL
with a clock and a
locking glove compartment

08:37.000 --> 08:40.280
for the sales director.

08:40.320 --> 08:46.160
And the powerful GT
for the managing director.

08:46.200 --> 08:51.880
Ford's badging policy quite
literally changed the class
system in Britain.

08:51.880 --> 08:55.280
Because we used to judge
people on how they held
their knife and fork,

08:55.320 --> 08:57.240
or whether they said
toilet or lavatory.

08:57.280 --> 08:59.280
But after
the Cortina came along,

08:59.320 --> 09:02.760
it was all based on what
it said on your boot lid.

09:04.880 --> 09:07.960
Our dads understood
what these badges meant.

09:08.000 --> 09:11.600
And boy, oh, boy, so did we.

09:13.640 --> 09:15.480
♪ HOVIS THEME TUNE

09:18.520 --> 09:21.400
You join me in Doncaster
outside my old school.

09:21.440 --> 09:23.200
And I remember very clearly

09:23.240 --> 09:25.400
coming out of that door
one afternoon in 1969,

09:25.440 --> 09:30.880
skipping along here, coming
round this gatepost here,

09:30.960 --> 09:33.760
and I noticed
that parked over there

09:33.760 --> 09:37.160
was a 1600E - an E -
in amber gold.

09:37.200 --> 09:39.320
Just like that one.

09:39.360 --> 09:42.640
And in it...was my dad.

09:44.080 --> 09:45.760
And that was impossible.

09:47.480 --> 09:50.760
The E was the absolute
king of the hill.

09:50.840 --> 09:54.520
It had four dials
set into its wooden dash.

09:54.600 --> 09:58.600
It had a leather and
aluminium steering wheel.

09:58.640 --> 10:00.760
And on the outside
there were Rostyle wheels

10:00.840 --> 10:04.040
and front fog lamps.

10:04.080 --> 10:06.880
It was beautiful and wondrous

10:06.960 --> 10:09.160
and exciting beyond words.

10:09.200 --> 10:11.120
(FLASHBULB POPS)

10:13.280 --> 10:17.720
I can still remember now,
vividly, how I felt.

10:17.760 --> 10:20.840
My knees actually buckled.

10:22.280 --> 10:24.360
I mean...

10:24.400 --> 10:27.840
The hairs on the back of
my neck are rising now

10:27.880 --> 10:33.640
in exactly the same way as
they did on that autumn day
50 years ago.

10:33.640 --> 10:37.040
I can also remember
the enormity of the hug
I gave my dad,

10:37.080 --> 10:39.640
cos I was just
so proud of him.

10:39.720 --> 10:44.320
I mean, he had an E!
An E stood for Executive.

10:44.360 --> 10:48.720
My dad had a 1600E.

10:48.760 --> 10:52.160
I mean, that meant
he was better than
the Duke of Edinburgh.

10:55.240 --> 10:56.840
(CHORAL SINGING)

10:56.880 --> 10:59.160
A few years later
in South Wales,

10:59.200 --> 11:01.960
another young boy
called James May

11:02.000 --> 11:06.000
went through
the exact same thing.

11:06.040 --> 11:09.200
I was at my mate
Andrew Jones's house,
just up the road from ours,

11:09.240 --> 11:12.080
when his dad came in
and said that my dad

11:12.120 --> 11:15.680
had just arrived home
and he had a new car.

11:15.720 --> 11:18.120
So, I went outside...

11:18.160 --> 11:21.200
and there
parked next to the kerb,

11:21.240 --> 11:24.480
was a brand-new Cortina GXL.

11:24.520 --> 11:27.600
And I thought, "Well, that
can't be my dad's new car."

11:29.480 --> 11:30.800
But it was.

11:33.840 --> 11:37.760
This was the all-new
Mark III Cortina.

11:37.800 --> 11:40.520
And, because it was
the GXL model,

11:40.560 --> 11:43.040
it had chrome strips
on the grille,

11:43.080 --> 11:45.000
and a vinyl roof.

11:45.040 --> 11:49.000
And four auxiliary dials
that were angled
towards the driver.

11:50.720 --> 11:53.120
It also had something
called a rev counter,

11:53.160 --> 11:55.400
and I'd never seen
one of those before.

11:55.440 --> 11:58.000
But when I looked at it,

11:58.040 --> 12:01.560
I suddenly became aware that
my body could produce semen.

12:04.680 --> 12:07.440
Unfortunately,
not all children in Britain

12:07.480 --> 12:09.640
were as fortunate
as James and me.

12:11.520 --> 12:13.960
Because some of them
were born in Birmingham.

12:21.800 --> 12:24.200
And you couldn't really
have a Ford here

12:24.240 --> 12:27.320
because this was the home
of British Leyland.

12:35.840 --> 12:37.960
RICHARD: I grew up here
on this street.

12:38.000 --> 12:41.320
And I remember the day my dad
came home with our new car.

12:41.360 --> 12:45.080
I prayed it would be
a Cortina. Literally prayed.

12:45.120 --> 12:47.080
But it wasn't.

12:47.120 --> 12:49.960
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

12:50.000 --> 12:52.680
What it was...
was a shoulder-sagging

12:52.720 --> 12:54.720
bag of disappointment

12:54.760 --> 12:57.480
called the
Austin Allegro Estate.

12:59.000 --> 13:01.600
It doesn't even have
four doors.

13:01.640 --> 13:04.520
What was my father thinking?

13:04.560 --> 13:06.200
Why did he do that to us?

13:06.240 --> 13:07.880
I fell to my childish knees,

13:07.920 --> 13:10.640
threw my head back
and I howled at the sky.

13:10.680 --> 13:13.320
Birds across Birmingham
took off.

13:13.360 --> 13:15.680
Deer in Stratford-upon-Avon
looked up.

13:15.720 --> 13:17.160
Such was my horror.

13:17.200 --> 13:20.720
This was the summit.
This was it!

13:20.760 --> 13:23.160
This is the best that we,
the Hammonds, could do.

13:23.200 --> 13:26.080
We lived in suburbia. People
drive past all the time.

13:26.120 --> 13:29.720
They see your car.
They judge you if have
a wishing well or a gate.

13:29.760 --> 13:32.320
We had this! On our drive!

13:32.360 --> 13:33.880
Where people could see it.

13:35.680 --> 13:37.440
Because my dad had the GXL

13:37.480 --> 13:42.560
he got the brake servo and
the alternator as standard.

13:42.600 --> 13:45.240
I'm sorry to keep banging on
about this GXL thing,

13:45.280 --> 13:49.080
but my mate Lonnie,
his dad only had an XL.

13:49.120 --> 13:50.760
So he was scum.

13:52.160 --> 13:54.160
I walked home from school.

13:54.200 --> 13:56.440
That wasn't cos
I wanted the exercise.

13:56.480 --> 14:00.160
That's because I would rather
walk or hop or crawl 30 miles

14:00.200 --> 14:02.600
than be seen
getting into that.

14:03.880 --> 14:05.880
It's cars like this,

14:05.920 --> 14:08.200
it's secrets,
dark secrets like this

14:08.240 --> 14:10.240
lurking in people's pasts

14:10.280 --> 14:12.720
that creates serial killers
and psychopaths.

14:12.760 --> 14:15.480
It's a bloody miracle
I'm not one.

14:15.520 --> 14:17.760
It's not being short that
makes me an angry man,

14:17.800 --> 14:21.840
or being born in Birmingham,
it's this! It's you!

14:21.880 --> 14:23.680
-(SMASHING)
-I could have been great,

14:23.720 --> 14:26.760
I could have had dignity,
social standing.

14:26.800 --> 14:29.600
I could have mattered.
But you came into my life...

14:32.200 --> 14:35.400
My dad bought
a Mark III Cortina

14:35.440 --> 14:37.120
because he had three children

14:37.160 --> 14:38.840
and he wanted them
to be safe.

14:38.880 --> 14:40.240
And he knew
they would be safe,

14:40.280 --> 14:42.720
because Ford had
made a film telling him so.

14:42.760 --> 14:45.120
We've got the teddy bears in,
we've got the golf clubs.

14:45.160 --> 14:47.000
-(CHILD CRYING)
-We've got the racing car.

14:47.040 --> 14:49.360
And if you don't happen
to carry those things

14:49.400 --> 14:51.000
but you have a bigger family,

14:51.040 --> 14:52.960
you can pack
those in as well.

14:53.000 --> 14:55.040
Even with five children
in the back,

14:55.080 --> 14:57.720
you can drive in a more
or less relaxed fashion,

14:57.760 --> 15:00.960
safe in the knowledge
that they're kept in
the four-door Cortina

15:01.000 --> 15:02.920
with child-proof
safety locks.

15:02.960 --> 15:04.880
I've never driven one
of these before,

15:04.920 --> 15:06.720
and to be honest,
I never wanted to,

15:06.760 --> 15:09.680
because that really would be
meeting a childhood hero.

15:11.240 --> 15:14.720
I love it, though. It's...

15:14.760 --> 15:17.160
(CRIES OUT) You can see
even better now, can't you?

15:17.200 --> 15:19.920
What about this one?
That's it.

15:19.960 --> 15:21.640
(INSECTS CHIRRUPING)

15:21.680 --> 15:23.000
(OWL HOOTS)

15:23.040 --> 15:25.640
Back in 1974, we used to have
regular power cuts

15:25.680 --> 15:27.120
because of
the miners' strike,

15:27.160 --> 15:29.160
and there was
absolutely nothing to do

15:29.200 --> 15:31.320
in our completely
pitch-black house.

15:31.360 --> 15:33.400
So I used to go outside
and sit in my dad's car

15:33.440 --> 15:36.120
and just pretend to drive it,
which was brilliant.

15:36.160 --> 15:38.440
Not least because
you could turn the light on,

15:38.480 --> 15:40.280
which you couldn't do
in the house.

15:42.720 --> 15:44.400
(HUMS)

15:44.440 --> 15:46.160
Lights. (HUMS)

15:46.200 --> 15:48.920
(CONTINUES HUMMING)

15:48.960 --> 15:51.600
Oh, I used to love
the power cuts.

15:51.640 --> 15:53.800
Outside of Birmingham, then,

15:53.840 --> 15:55.800
everyone young and old
was in love

15:55.840 --> 15:57.760
with Ford's four-door saloon.

15:59.640 --> 16:01.400
Because of this love affair,

16:01.440 --> 16:08.560
Ford sold a Cortina somewhere
in Britain every 47 seconds.

16:08.600 --> 16:12.880
In 20 years, they sold
2.6 million of them.

16:12.920 --> 16:14.680
And let me put it this way:

16:14.720 --> 16:17.840
British Leyland took
twice as long as that

16:17.880 --> 16:20.680
to sell half as many Minis.

16:20.720 --> 16:22.640
(UPLIFTING CLASSICAL MUSIC)

16:24.840 --> 16:29.480
The Cortina then
had become a part of
the fabric of Britain.

16:29.520 --> 16:32.800
It was the nitrogen
of our existence.

16:35.200 --> 16:39.120
But, on 22nd July 1982...

16:41.000 --> 16:43.280
...Ford pulled the plug.

16:43.320 --> 16:44.920
(MUSIC DISTORTS AND SLOWS)

16:44.960 --> 16:47.360
And that was the end of that.

16:49.080 --> 16:50.920
(CHEERING)

16:50.960 --> 16:52.800
-Sad story of the Cortina.
-Yeah, it is.

16:52.840 --> 16:54.800
-But it's a great story.
-It goes on.

16:54.840 --> 16:56.640
-Yeah.
-Do you feel better?

16:56.680 --> 16:59.680
-Um...yeah. A bit.
-That's good.

16:59.720 --> 17:02.280
I just want to do...
I just want to do one thing.

17:02.320 --> 17:05.800
Can I just ask,
how many people's dads
here had Cortinas?

17:05.840 --> 17:08.120
This is... Look at that.
JAMES: Yeah.

17:08.160 --> 17:09.920
That's an astonishing array,
isn't it?

17:09.960 --> 17:12.480
-Amazing. (CHUCKLES)
-Yes, it is.

17:12.520 --> 17:15.560
It makes me feel really--
Just to put some
perspective on this.

17:15.640 --> 17:18.560
-Ford sold
2.6 million Cortinas.
-Hm.

17:18.560 --> 17:20.560
Austin... (CLEARS THROAT)

17:20.640 --> 17:24.920
-...sold 57,000 Allegro
Estates. That's it.
-(LAUGHTER)

17:24.960 --> 17:27.720
-It's a shame
one of them was to your dad.
-You're damn right!

17:27.760 --> 17:29.520
It ruined my life.

17:29.560 --> 17:31.680
Anyway, we shall pick up
the Ford story later on.

17:31.720 --> 17:34.680
But now it is time
for us to deploy

17:34.720 --> 17:37.240
the plastic bag of chat,

17:37.280 --> 17:39.440
to scoop up
some dog eggs of debate...

17:39.480 --> 17:43.800
-(LAUGHTER)
-...from the pavements of
Conversation Street.

17:43.880 --> 17:47.080
(MELLOW JAZZ
SEGUES INTO TECHNO)

17:48.200 --> 17:50.400
(BURST OF SAXOPHONE)

17:50.440 --> 17:51.800
(CHEERING)

17:51.800 --> 17:54.680
JEREMY: Wow.
-I don't know. I don't know.

17:54.720 --> 17:56.880
-Whatever it was.
JAMES: Er...

17:59.280 --> 18:03.000
Now actually, despite
the incredible snazziness
of those graphics,

18:03.040 --> 18:04.680
we don't actually have time

18:04.720 --> 18:07.080
-for traditional Conversation
Street this week.
-No.

18:07.080 --> 18:08.960
Because we are engaged,
as we said,

18:09.000 --> 18:11.200
-in important
documentary-making work.
-We are.

18:11.240 --> 18:12.960
Which is why
I would like to talk about

18:13.000 --> 18:14.760
-body-coloured bumpers.
-Ooh!

18:14.800 --> 18:17.760
-I think you should.
-Yes, I will,
because in the old days,

18:17.800 --> 18:20.720
if you were driving
up the motorway and
a car came up behind you,

18:20.760 --> 18:24.520
and they had bumpers
the same colour as the car,

18:24.560 --> 18:26.400
and you only had
black plastic bumpers,

18:26.440 --> 18:27.960
you knew you had
to get out of the way.

18:28.000 --> 18:29.560
-You did.
-They were better than you.

18:29.640 --> 18:32.080
Yeah, they were better
than you because of that.

18:32.080 --> 18:34.480
What if you were
driving up the motorway,

18:34.520 --> 18:36.400
looked in the rear-view
mirror, OK,

18:36.440 --> 18:39.560
and you saw the car behind
had head restraints?

18:39.640 --> 18:41.520
(BOTH GASP)

18:41.560 --> 18:43.800
Honestly, head restraints,

18:43.880 --> 18:46.080
I used to look at those
in the way people these days

18:46.160 --> 18:47.760
look at superyachts.

18:47.800 --> 18:50.440
They were simply
unattainable. I mean,
you could not...

18:50.480 --> 18:52.200
These were
the symbols of rank.

18:52.240 --> 18:54.320
-I mean,
if you had a sun roof...
JEREMY: Oh!

18:54.320 --> 18:55.880
...you were an emperor.

18:55.920 --> 18:57.320
(LAUGHTER)

18:57.320 --> 19:00.000
What if...it was
an electric sun roof?

19:00.040 --> 19:01.560
Oh, my God!

19:01.640 --> 19:05.520
You were probably from space,
you were a space emperor!

19:05.560 --> 19:07.680
Let me see if I can explain
this in a language

19:07.720 --> 19:09.240
people under 40
understand, OK?

19:09.280 --> 19:11.000
It's the same
as going for a job, OK,

19:11.040 --> 19:13.480
and your boss saying, "We're
gonna give you a pay cut,

19:13.520 --> 19:15.800
but we're gonna give you
a phone, OK?

19:15.800 --> 19:17.920
And this phone
you can use to make calls,

19:17.960 --> 19:20.400
and then if you work
really hard
for a couple of years,

19:20.440 --> 19:23.520
we'll give you
an iPhone L,

19:23.560 --> 19:26.320
and you can use that
to make texts as well.

19:26.320 --> 19:27.920
And then if you stay
with us for 30 years,

19:27.960 --> 19:29.280
and you never put
a foot wrong,

19:29.320 --> 19:31.640
you can have an iPhone GXL."

19:31.680 --> 19:35.320
Because that's what...
I mean, I have no idea
which one this is.

19:35.400 --> 19:38.480
-No, is it a 7,
an 8, a 9? I don't know.
-No, you don't know.

19:38.520 --> 19:41.560
But the thing is,
under 1970s rules,
you would have known,

19:41.560 --> 19:44.800
because that would have
had a great big chrome
GXL badge on.

19:44.880 --> 19:47.160
And a chrome strip round the
outside and fog lights here.

19:47.200 --> 19:50.160
-Yeah, exactly,
so you would know.
-They were the badges of rank

19:50.200 --> 19:52.800
and everybody could see them.
That was the world
we lived in.

19:52.800 --> 19:55.080
My dad, right,
when he had the 1600E,

19:55.080 --> 19:57.400
he had a minor front-end
biff in it, yes?

19:57.440 --> 20:02.000
The local Ford garage
replaced the damaged grille
with one from a 1600 Super.

20:02.040 --> 20:04.040
And my dad said,
"Oh, it doesn't matter."

20:04.080 --> 20:08.080
But it did! It was
more important than
the Vietnam War!

20:08.160 --> 20:11.040
-I mean, it...
-You were being...
being publicly humiliated.

20:11.080 --> 20:14.760
People were going, "You
haven't got a 1600E, there's
chrome..." It is a 1600E!

20:14.800 --> 20:16.800
"You just put fog lights
on." We haven't!

20:16.800 --> 20:19.400
-We've really got one!
-These things
mattered so much.

20:19.440 --> 20:22.720
-Oh, they really did.
-Didn't... You had a 1600E?

20:22.760 --> 20:26.080
Oh, we did. No, ten years
after my dad sold his,
I bought one.

20:26.160 --> 20:28.280
-Well done,
that was imaginative.
-It was--

20:28.320 --> 20:31.280
Says the man
whose first car was?

20:31.320 --> 20:34.880
-Toyota Corolla?
-It was a Liftback, actually.

20:34.920 --> 20:38.760
Yeah, but my 1600E,
I modified it, and put...

20:38.800 --> 20:41.280
I put a Debbie Harry badge
in the middle of
the steering wheel.

20:41.320 --> 20:43.960
-(LAUGHTER)
-Fur-lined doors...

20:44.000 --> 20:46.320
-Ooh!
-Wolfrace seats...

20:46.320 --> 20:50.760
And a chromed sports
air filter, which I told
me mates,

20:50.800 --> 20:54.080
"That gives extra 40
horsepower, that does."
It didn't. Not really.

20:54.160 --> 20:56.760
-But I told my mates it did.
-Do you know
what you did there?

20:56.800 --> 20:58.320
-What?
-By fitting those extra bits

20:58.320 --> 21:00.400
like the sports air filter
onto your car,

21:00.440 --> 21:04.520
you were effectively calling
yourself Jeremy Clarkson OBE

21:04.560 --> 21:06.720
-when you didn't have one.
-It is a bit like that.

21:06.760 --> 21:10.800
With those fur-lined doors
you had interfered with
the class system.

21:10.800 --> 21:13.680
Mm, mm. But let's not forget,
shall we,

21:13.720 --> 21:17.440
you modified your Corolla
by driving it into a Volvo.

21:17.480 --> 21:19.280
-Yeah, I did.
-(LAUGHTER)

21:19.320 --> 21:21.720
I did do that,
it was my first crash.

21:21.760 --> 21:23.920
-The first of many.
-Yes, all right. Yes.

21:23.960 --> 21:27.000
-Rather set the trend
for your life, didn't it?
-I got the hang of it.

21:27.040 --> 21:29.720
-Yes. Yes, OK.
-"I like crashing, I'll make
a living out of this.

21:29.760 --> 21:31.560
-There I go again."
-And I did.

21:31.640 --> 21:32.800
(LAUGHTER)

21:33.920 --> 21:35.760
JEREMY: Exactly.

21:37.080 --> 21:40.160
Oh, God.

21:40.200 --> 21:43.000
Do you know, I've... I've
never actually owned a Ford.

21:43.040 --> 21:44.320
-What, never?
-No.

21:44.320 --> 21:46.680
That's like saying you've
never owned your own pen.

21:46.720 --> 21:48.400
I've never bought a stamp.

21:48.440 --> 21:51.080
-I mean, even I
have managed to own a Ford.
-Really?

21:51.160 --> 21:55.240
After I left Birmingham,
I moved on, and I had two.

21:55.280 --> 21:57.080
But sort of in the same car.

21:57.120 --> 22:00.440
The front... front of one and
the back of the other joined.

22:00.480 --> 22:03.680
-It was absolutely hopeless.
-Were they the same colour?

22:03.720 --> 22:07.160
Well, when I bought them,
broadly similar,
yes, they were.

22:07.200 --> 22:09.800
Look, this is,
it's not really
Conversation Street, is it?

22:09.840 --> 22:11.280
-No.
-It's more Memory Lane.

22:11.320 --> 22:13.920
Anyway, we now have
to get back to the Cortina.

22:13.960 --> 22:17.680
Yes, we do, because when
it was killed off in 1982,

22:17.720 --> 22:21.080
Ford didn't give up
on the idea of a
multi-million-selling

22:21.120 --> 22:23.000
medium-sized family saloon,

22:23.040 --> 22:25.080
they came up
with a replacement.

22:25.120 --> 22:27.120
It was called the Sierra.

22:27.160 --> 22:29.600
Here is a picture of it.
And, to begin with,

22:29.640 --> 22:31.920
-it was a bit of a lemon,
wasn't it?
-It was.

22:31.960 --> 22:33.680
When it came out,
everybody said they hated

22:33.720 --> 22:36.680
its kind of futuristic,
aerodynamic shape.

22:36.720 --> 22:38.880
They said it looked horrid,
like a jelly mould.

22:38.920 --> 22:40.840
And then everybody worked out

22:40.880 --> 22:43.360
the aerodynamics
didn't even work.

22:43.400 --> 22:45.480
No, it turned out in a
straight line it was fine,

22:45.520 --> 22:46.960
but when it got hit
by a crosswind,

22:47.000 --> 22:49.240
or would overtake a truck
on the motorway,

22:49.280 --> 22:50.960
it would veer about
like a drunk.

22:51.000 --> 22:54.320
Yeah, another problem
was the motor trade hated it

22:54.360 --> 22:57.240
because that plastic front
end, if you had a crash,

22:57.280 --> 22:59.680
it would boing back into
shape, which was brilliant.

22:59.720 --> 23:04.760
But you didn't know that
everything behind it was
actually smashed to pieces.

23:04.800 --> 23:06.920
Now, Ford decided
there was only one way

23:06.960 --> 23:10.520
to get everybody to
fall in love with its new
mid-sized family saloon.

23:10.560 --> 23:12.680
It was something
they'd done before.

23:12.720 --> 23:14.120
Make a fast version.

23:15.880 --> 23:18.280
RICHARD: What they
came up with was this...

23:21.200 --> 23:23.920
...the Sierra RS Cosworth.

23:26.080 --> 23:29.960
A car that could do
150 miles an hour.

23:30.000 --> 23:31.640
(ENGINE REVS)

23:34.680 --> 23:36.520
(TYRES SCREECHING)

23:41.280 --> 23:47.880
It was 1986. Lots of cars
could do 150, but not a Ford.

23:47.920 --> 23:51.640
That was madness.
BMW and Mercedes
could not believe it.

23:51.680 --> 23:56.120
This was the gardener coming
into the parlour and kicking
the baron's teeth out.

23:59.840 --> 24:02.840
The blue-bloods were being
absolutely battered by this -

24:02.880 --> 24:05.040
the blue-collar worker.

24:05.080 --> 24:06.920
(ENGINE REVS)

24:10.200 --> 24:12.640
The Sierra's muscle
came from Cosworth.

24:13.800 --> 24:15.320
The British engine builder

24:15.360 --> 24:17.760
whose most famous
Formula One V8

24:17.800 --> 24:22.360
had taken a staggering
176 Grand Prix victories.

24:24.360 --> 24:27.680
They took a drab,
cast-iron saloon car engine

24:27.720 --> 24:30.320
and fitted it with an
aluminium twin-cam head,

24:30.360 --> 24:33.280
a turbo
the size of a dustbin,

24:33.320 --> 24:36.360
and turned it
into a masterpiece.

24:40.200 --> 24:42.840
It was built to be
a hard-working unit, this.

24:42.880 --> 24:44.560
As you can tell.

24:44.600 --> 24:47.480
The interesting thing
about this engine,
is if you look carefully

24:47.520 --> 24:49.480
you can see there's
a second set of injectors

24:49.520 --> 24:51.880
that weren't actually
connected to anything.

24:51.920 --> 24:55.520
They were installed because
Ford knew they'd be necessary

24:55.560 --> 24:59.080
when they did
what they always did
with their family cars...

24:59.120 --> 25:01.040
go racing with them.

25:03.440 --> 25:07.280
With those injectors engaged,
and bigger turbos fitted,

25:07.320 --> 25:13.680
the race cars were churning
out a massive 525 horsepower.

25:15.040 --> 25:17.920
They were unstoppable.

25:17.960 --> 25:19.920
COMMENTATOR:
The Ford Sierra Cosworth,

25:19.960 --> 25:23.320
the top touring car
of the day.

25:23.360 --> 25:26.160
RICHARD: In its day,
the Sierra won 84%

25:26.200 --> 25:28.080
of races it entered.

25:28.120 --> 25:31.320
84%.

25:31.360 --> 25:35.120
And that makes it
the most successful
racing car ever made.

25:38.000 --> 25:41.200
I'd love to meet a driver who
raced one and didn't win.

25:41.240 --> 25:44.400
"Right, so I had absolutely
the best tool for the job,

25:44.440 --> 25:47.280
and everyone else
has won with it except me.

25:47.320 --> 25:48.960
I'm fired, aren't I?"

25:55.200 --> 25:57.600
To keep the
road-going rocket ship

25:57.640 --> 26:00.240
pointing mostly
in the right direction,

26:00.280 --> 26:04.320
it got beefed-up suspension,
a limited slip diff,

26:04.360 --> 26:06.120
and its most
famous feature...

26:08.600 --> 26:10.920
...that massive back wing.

26:10.960 --> 26:13.400
And that wing says everything
about the Cosworth.

26:13.440 --> 26:16.720
Compared with grown-up things
from Mercedes and BMW,

26:16.760 --> 26:18.560
it said, "Ah, sod off!

26:18.600 --> 26:21.760
I don't care
what you think about me."

26:21.800 --> 26:23.560
(TYRES SCREECH)

26:23.600 --> 26:24.960
But it was also there
for a reason,

26:25.000 --> 26:27.840
to make actual downforce.

26:27.880 --> 26:30.160
Which, according
to men called Gav

26:30.200 --> 26:32.120
in every flat-roof pub
in the country,

26:32.160 --> 26:34.320
meant the Sierra
could drive upside-down

26:34.360 --> 26:36.280
on the roof of a tunnel.

26:40.040 --> 26:41.400
I'm not sure about that.

26:41.440 --> 26:43.240
This thing
is still pretty lively.

26:43.280 --> 26:45.400
(TYRES SCREECHING)

27:00.600 --> 27:02.520
Ha-ha, ha-ha!

27:04.600 --> 27:06.200
It brings out
the worst in you.

27:06.240 --> 27:08.600
This is like
a really bad mate.

27:08.640 --> 27:10.320
You know,
the one you absolutely love

27:10.360 --> 27:14.000
but nobody appreciates you
hanging around with him.

27:16.720 --> 27:21.280
Cosworth turned the Sierra
into one of the most
desirable cars on the planet.

27:23.200 --> 27:25.360
And because
it only cost 17 grand,

27:25.400 --> 27:28.520
six grand less
than a BMW M3,

27:28.560 --> 27:30.200
your local builder
could have one.

27:30.240 --> 27:32.040
(ENGINE REVS)

27:32.080 --> 27:36.880
However, while everyone
wanted Ford's latest
working-class hero,

27:36.920 --> 27:40.200
not everyone was
prepared to pay for it.

27:40.240 --> 27:41.840
-Joy riders...
-Joy riders...

27:41.880 --> 27:44.480
Joy riders in a stolen
Sierra Cosworth...

27:44.520 --> 27:47.000
...driving around a
Newcastle housing estate...

27:47.040 --> 27:49.800
The high-performance vehicle
is the twoccer's favourite.

27:49.840 --> 27:50.880
(SMASHING)

27:50.920 --> 27:52.200
(POLICE SIREN WAILS)

27:52.240 --> 27:53.560
In the late '80s,

27:53.600 --> 27:56.040
car crime saw
a massive spike.

27:56.080 --> 27:59.040
And the Cosworth
was at its tip.

27:59.080 --> 28:02.360
(WINDSCREEN WIPER SQUEAKING)

28:02.400 --> 28:04.960
Here was a car with the
performance of a supercar

28:05.000 --> 28:08.080
and the locks of a shed.

28:08.120 --> 28:10.360
If you had five seconds
and a screwdriver,

28:10.400 --> 28:12.520
you too could have
a Sierra Cosworth.

28:12.560 --> 28:15.440
And whatever you did next,
the fuzz couldn't catch you.

28:18.160 --> 28:20.160
Ford tried to get
on top of things,

28:20.200 --> 28:22.000
by stripping off the wing,

28:22.040 --> 28:23.640
and putting
the firecracker engine

28:23.680 --> 28:26.800
into a sober,
four-door shell...

28:26.840 --> 28:29.440
...to make this the Sierra
Sapphire Cosworth.

28:30.920 --> 28:32.680
But it didn't work.

28:32.720 --> 28:34.560
(SOUNDTRACK MUSIC
GRINDS TO A HALT)

28:34.600 --> 28:36.600
If anything,
the crims were grateful.

28:36.640 --> 28:38.240
"Oh, thanks, back doors.

28:38.280 --> 28:40.960
Makes it easier for the lads
to get in after a bank job."

28:41.000 --> 28:42.920
But ultimately... What?

28:48.280 --> 28:50.200
Oh, for God's sake!

28:53.600 --> 28:55.640
Things got so bad
by the early '90s

28:55.680 --> 28:59.840
that the Sierra Cosworth was
five-and-half times more
likely to be stolen

28:59.880 --> 29:02.320
than any other car.

29:02.360 --> 29:05.560
There were many owners
who reported being followed
by criminals,

29:05.600 --> 29:09.080
waiting for them to park
so they could nick it.

29:09.120 --> 29:12.040
That would take the edge off
the pleasure of owning it,
if I'm honest.

29:13.200 --> 29:14.960
Ford got so desperate,

29:15.000 --> 29:18.400
they dropped the price
of the Cosworth by £7,000 -

29:18.440 --> 29:21.000
the value of
an entire Fiesta -

29:21.040 --> 29:23.040
just to shift the things.

29:23.080 --> 29:26.120
And even that didn't work.

29:26.160 --> 29:29.200
There were numerous reports
at the time
of Cosworth owners

29:29.240 --> 29:33.080
receiving insurance quotes
that were more than
the value of the car.

29:33.120 --> 29:35.640
And eventually,
insuring a Sierra Cosworth

29:35.680 --> 29:38.760
became not just expensive
but impossible.

29:38.800 --> 29:40.720
They were uninsurable.

29:43.800 --> 29:45.720
But by then,
it didn't matter.

29:47.720 --> 29:49.840
The Sierra Cosworth
had done its job,

29:49.880 --> 29:54.480
just as the Lotus Cortina
had done 25 years earlier,

29:54.520 --> 29:59.160
by making an ordinary family
saloon seem impossibly cool.

30:03.000 --> 30:04.920
(TYRES SCREECHING)

30:15.040 --> 30:16.920
Honestly,
I was flipping drooling.

30:16.960 --> 30:18.840
-It's a legend of a car.
-Absolute legend.

30:18.880 --> 30:20.880
I was drooling, watching.

30:20.920 --> 30:23.360
I absolutely loved...

30:23.400 --> 30:25.680
I adored the Sierra Cosworth.

30:25.720 --> 30:27.440
-It was brilliant.
-Fabulous.

30:27.480 --> 30:31.720
Absolutely fabulous, but
I need to do a bit more
documentary work.

30:31.760 --> 30:34.560
-I think you should.
-The Cosworth wasn't
the most important thing

30:34.600 --> 30:37.760
about the Sierra.
The most important thing was,

30:37.800 --> 30:40.160
the Sierra changed
the Labour Party.

30:40.200 --> 30:42.800
-Really?
-It genuinely did.

30:42.840 --> 30:45.440
A young Tony Blair
was out canvassing one day,

30:45.480 --> 30:47.920
saw a man washing
his Sierra on the drive,

30:47.960 --> 30:49.680
sort of went up to him.

30:49.720 --> 30:52.560
The Labour Party policy
back then, as now, actually,

30:52.600 --> 30:55.760
was to get the man out of
his car and back where
he belonged on a bus.

30:55.800 --> 30:59.160
-Yes.
-Tony Blair realised this guy
didn't want to go on a bus.

30:59.200 --> 31:02.560
He wanted a better Sierra,
faster Sierra,
Sierra with headrests.

31:02.600 --> 31:04.880
So he went away and
he created New Labour

31:04.920 --> 31:06.840
as a result
of that conversation.

31:06.880 --> 31:08.800
And then started
an illegal war.

31:08.840 --> 31:10.640
(LAUGHTER)

31:12.120 --> 31:13.360
Well, he did.

31:13.400 --> 31:14.800
Well...

31:14.840 --> 31:16.560
-Well, he did.
-(APPLAUSE)

31:16.600 --> 31:19.400
JEREMY: He did. He did.

31:19.440 --> 31:20.880
(CHUCKLING)

31:20.920 --> 31:23.560
He did do those... He did do
those two things, yes.

31:23.600 --> 31:25.200
Should we get
back to the car?

31:25.240 --> 31:28.120
Good idea, because we must
now find out how fast...

31:28.160 --> 31:30.640
Let's see if I can still
pronounce it properly.

31:30.680 --> 31:32.800
-...the Cozzer...
-Yeah, you've still got it.

31:32.840 --> 31:34.720
The Cozzer. You know
what I mean? The Cozzer.

31:34.760 --> 31:38.960
Let's see how fast it goes
round the Eboladrome.

31:39.000 --> 31:41.200
And away it goes,
gentle off the line,

31:41.240 --> 31:45.040
but then a scuff of wheel
spin as the turbo
roars into life

31:45.080 --> 31:48.000
and catapults it
onto the Isn't.

31:50.240 --> 31:52.840
The 1980s gear change
workout there,

31:52.880 --> 31:56.960
and a lot of body roll
on those soft '80s springs.

32:00.320 --> 32:01.840
Ooh, look at that!

32:01.880 --> 32:03.440
Driving it like it's stolen,

32:03.480 --> 32:05.680
which 30 years ago,
it would have been.

32:05.720 --> 32:08.800
Here we go,
ooh, yeah, bit of oversteer
into Your Name Here.

32:08.840 --> 32:11.800
You don't see that
from the modern stuff.

32:11.840 --> 32:13.480
And now the turbo lag clears

32:13.520 --> 32:16.000
as it fires back down
the Isn't.

32:16.040 --> 32:18.800
This won't be the fastest car
we've ever seen,

32:18.840 --> 32:22.840
but I can bet you Abbie
is having an absolute riot
in there.

32:25.080 --> 32:27.440
OK, hard braking
for Old Lady's House,

32:27.480 --> 32:29.360
wrestling it in,
keeping it neat

32:29.400 --> 32:31.520
through the right,
and then the left.

32:31.560 --> 32:35.640
And now back on the power
for the blast to Substation.

32:35.680 --> 32:38.360
Engine note that screams,
"Oi, Gary!"

32:38.400 --> 32:42.400
That's it, braking, flicks it
in like a touring car driver.

32:42.440 --> 32:44.600
Only Field of Sheep left.

32:44.640 --> 32:48.400
Not much drama there,
and across the line!

32:48.440 --> 32:50.760
That looks great,
looks really exciting.

32:50.800 --> 32:53.240
I was really expecting
the full crossed up...

32:53.280 --> 32:55.600
No, but that...it does that
four-wheel drift thing,

32:55.640 --> 32:58.040
same as the Lotus Cortina,
wah!

32:58.080 --> 33:00.480
-It's what they do.
-Anyway, let's see now

33:00.520 --> 33:04.000
how quickly Abbie got it
round the Eboladrome.

33:04.040 --> 33:06.960
Let's find out the time -
oh, quicker than I thought.

33:07.000 --> 33:08.480
Oh-ho!

33:08.520 --> 33:10.000
-(JAMES LAUGHS)
JEREMY: What?

33:10.040 --> 33:11.840
Well, it's faster
than a Lamborghini.

33:11.880 --> 33:13.760
(LAUGHTER)

33:13.800 --> 33:15.440
I told you
that thing was slow,

33:15.480 --> 33:17.880
it's actually
slower than a Ford Sierra.

33:17.920 --> 33:20.120
But the interesting thing
for me there

33:20.160 --> 33:23.360
is it's quicker than
a Ford Fiesta ST200,

33:23.400 --> 33:25.920
and they both have the same
power, about 200 horsepower.

33:25.960 --> 33:28.400
They did, yeah.
I think what that goes
to show is,

33:28.440 --> 33:31.200
despite all the improvements
in suspension and tyres,

33:31.240 --> 33:34.440
you can't beat
fitting something with
a sodding great turbo.

33:34.480 --> 33:36.880
-Exactly.
-A massive turbo
does the job.

33:36.920 --> 33:39.920
Anyway, can I get back
to our documentary, yes?

33:39.960 --> 33:43.240
In 1993, Ford stopped
making the Sierra

33:43.280 --> 33:46.800
and decided instead
to export the idea

33:46.840 --> 33:50.480
that had revolutionised
Britain to the whole world.

33:50.520 --> 33:54.000
What they came up with
was something they called
a World Car.

33:54.040 --> 33:56.480
Something not just
for everyone here,

33:56.520 --> 33:58.360
but for everyone everywhere.

33:58.400 --> 34:00.400
They called it the Mondeo.

34:00.440 --> 34:05.640
And it achieved something
that no car in history
has ever managed.

34:10.280 --> 34:13.000
Over the years, Richard,
James and I have driven

34:13.040 --> 34:15.960
almost every car ever made.

34:19.640 --> 34:22.000
We've waxed lyrical
about many of them...

34:23.800 --> 34:25.800
...drooling over
their styling...

34:27.960 --> 34:30.760
...or their handling...

34:30.800 --> 34:34.520
...or the way they make the
roots of our penises fizz.

34:39.560 --> 34:44.200
But incredibly, there is only
one car that we all like.

34:48.360 --> 34:49.960
This one -

34:50.000 --> 34:52.680
the Mondeo ST Estate.

35:02.440 --> 35:05.640
Let's be clear,
there are lots of cars
we all don't like.

35:05.640 --> 35:07.320
-Yeah, yes.
-Nissan Juke.

35:07.360 --> 35:08.880
Hate it. The Beetle.

35:08.920 --> 35:11.320
Good one on the Beetle,
we all hate that.

35:11.360 --> 35:13.880
-Nissan "Quashquai".
-Yeah, that's a good one.

35:13.920 --> 35:15.800
Audi Q5.

35:15.840 --> 35:17.760
-No, don't like that.
-All hate that.

35:17.800 --> 35:20.160
-And the Q7.
-And the Q7.
We all hate that.

35:20.200 --> 35:22.560
-Jaguar X-Type.
-Yeah, we all hate that.

35:22.600 --> 35:24.400
The new Land Rover Discovery.

35:24.440 --> 35:25.640
-Yes.
-Yeah.

35:25.640 --> 35:27.040
BMW X3.

35:27.080 --> 35:28.160
-Yep, yeah.
-Yes.

35:28.160 --> 35:30.160
-Mini Countryman.
-Oh, yeah, yeah!

35:30.200 --> 35:33.600
We all hate that.

35:33.640 --> 35:36.920
So, we've established
there are many, many cars
we all don't like.

35:36.960 --> 35:38.840
But cars we do like?

35:38.880 --> 35:40.880
-There's this.
-There's this.

35:43.160 --> 35:45.520
RICHARD: What about
the Subaru Legacy Outback?

35:45.560 --> 35:47.160
But the front diff's rubbish.

35:47.200 --> 35:49.640
You can't go round a corner
when you're going slowly.

35:49.680 --> 35:51.760
-So it's a bit annoying.
-So it is just this?

35:51.800 --> 35:54.840
JEREMY: Yeah.
JAMES: This is it.

35:54.880 --> 35:58.600
Do you know what I liked?
It's the fast version,
but it was still comfortable.

35:58.640 --> 36:00.960
These seats were great.
It still rides properly.

36:01.000 --> 36:03.560
It doesn't make a terrible
racket, it's just civilised.

36:03.600 --> 36:05.640
RICHARD: I like the way
it was a practical estate.

36:05.680 --> 36:09.040
It had a massive boot,
and Ford had the sense
to give it five doors.

36:09.080 --> 36:11.760
Which is something
Austin didn't think of
with the Allegro.

36:11.800 --> 36:13.760
No, that is true.
I like the speed.

36:13.800 --> 36:15.160
Oh, there's a surprise.

36:15.160 --> 36:17.120
(ENGINE REVVING)

36:18.280 --> 36:20.160
V6 engine, 200 horsepower.

36:22.080 --> 36:26.160
0-60, seven seconds.
Top speed, 150.

36:26.160 --> 36:29.120
It didn't look it, but this
was as quick as a Cosworth.

36:32.560 --> 36:36.800
And when they turned it
into the ST220 in 2002,

36:36.840 --> 36:40.040
it looked right as well.

36:40.080 --> 36:42.480
They should have sold these
by the million.

36:43.600 --> 36:45.320
But there was a problem.

36:45.360 --> 36:46.680
(SOUNDTRACK STOPS ABRUPTLY)

36:49.120 --> 36:51.480
This.

36:51.520 --> 36:57.360
The first so-called MPV,
the Toyota Picnic.

36:57.400 --> 37:00.480
In 1996 when it was first
introduced, we laughed at it,

37:00.520 --> 37:03.320
because it seemed so stupid.

37:05.880 --> 37:09.960
I mean, why name a car
after something you
might do in it? Picnic.

37:10.000 --> 37:12.280
No, they didn't have
a Toyota Dentist, did they?

37:12.320 --> 37:15.880
The Honda Pop-to-the-Shops.
It's just an ordinary act,
it's not even exciting.

37:15.920 --> 37:17.640
The Volkswagen Dogging.

37:17.680 --> 37:19.320
-(CHUCKLING)
-It's just a stupid idea.

37:19.360 --> 37:20.960
A naff thing to do.

37:21.000 --> 37:25.120
It cost the same as a Mondeo,
it was just a bit taller.

37:25.160 --> 37:27.560
Yeah. It's in case your head
suddenly grows tall.

37:27.600 --> 37:29.120
Was there a fashion
for wearing

37:29.160 --> 37:31.640
Victorian industrialist hats
at the time?

37:31.640 --> 37:34.280
-No, there wasn't.
-Well, there's no excuse
for it, then.

37:34.320 --> 37:36.160
Unless you've actually
got a Busby

37:36.160 --> 37:39.040
glued to the top
of your head...

37:39.080 --> 37:40.800
RICHARD:
There is no other reason.

37:40.840 --> 37:42.960
And what troubles me,

37:43.000 --> 37:45.600
is think of the damage
this did to children.

37:45.640 --> 37:47.680
"Come out and see
the new car, kids!"

37:47.760 --> 37:50.400
(SQUEALS)

37:50.440 --> 37:53.440
-(LAUGHS) It's just a Picnic!
-"That...

37:53.480 --> 37:55.200
That's our car.

37:55.280 --> 37:56.600
It's hateful!"

37:56.640 --> 37:59.400
It's dismal.

37:59.440 --> 38:02.400
"It's got big windows so
people will see me in it."

38:02.440 --> 38:05.120
JAMES: It actually says,
"Family fun vehicle" on it.

38:05.160 --> 38:07.040
JEREMY: It doesn't?
What's fun about it?

38:07.080 --> 38:08.960
RICHARD: It isn't more fun.

38:09.000 --> 38:12.360
We thought,
when it first came along,
that it would be a fad,

38:12.400 --> 38:15.400
like culottes,
or deep fried brie,

38:15.440 --> 38:17.320
or Crocs, or tattoos.

38:17.360 --> 38:20.040
Something where you think,
"Oh, that's fun,"

38:20.080 --> 38:23.800
and then realise
five minutes later that
it's actually ridiculous.

38:24.920 --> 38:26.280
But, no.

38:26.320 --> 38:28.880
This idiotic tall car idea

38:28.920 --> 38:31.000
actually started to catch on.

38:34.040 --> 38:35.840
Renault came up
with their version,

38:35.880 --> 38:37.880
which was called
the Scenic.

38:37.920 --> 38:40.680
And pretty soon,
everyone was at it -

38:40.760 --> 38:43.960
Mazda, Fiat,
Vauxhall, the lot!

38:46.040 --> 38:48.600
RICHARD: Think what
you started, you bastard.

38:48.640 --> 38:50.840
You deserve this,
and you're having it.

38:51.960 --> 38:54.760
And you're having more of it.

38:54.800 --> 38:57.680
A new car is a great thing,
but not when it's you!

38:57.760 --> 38:59.640
Oh, you've got a mirror left.

39:01.200 --> 39:04.000
Think how many lives
you ruined.

39:04.040 --> 39:06.880
You are the Allegro Estate
of modern times,

39:06.920 --> 39:09.440
and you deserve this.

39:09.480 --> 39:11.960
To make matters worse
for Ford,

39:12.000 --> 39:15.120
in 2000, the British
Government decided
that company cars

39:15.160 --> 39:17.280
should be taxed,
like income.

39:17.320 --> 39:19.640
Yeah, that meant people
had to buy their own cars.

39:19.640 --> 39:22.880
And many responded
by not buying a car at all.

39:25.000 --> 39:26.760
As interest rates
were so low,

39:26.800 --> 39:29.520
it made more sense
to lease.

39:29.560 --> 39:32.000
And if you're gonna do that,
why not get a BMW?

39:33.480 --> 39:36.120
Or a Mercedes?

39:36.160 --> 39:38.520
As the rot
started to take hold,

39:38.560 --> 39:42.440
Ford reverted to type
and got serious
about motor racing.

39:49.840 --> 39:53.760
In 2000, they came first,
second and third

39:53.800 --> 39:56.160
in the British Touring Car
Championship.

39:56.200 --> 40:00.280
COMMENTATOR: All three Fords
were on the front row again
for the sprint race...

40:00.320 --> 40:04.400
JEREMY:
And the following year,
Mondeo sales did go up a bit.

40:04.440 --> 40:06.400
COMMENTATOR:
Ford drivers clocking ...

40:06.440 --> 40:10.880
JEREMY: But then,
they stopped motor racing.

40:10.920 --> 40:15.200
And the MPVs kept coming,
and leasing a Mercedes
got cheaper,

40:15.280 --> 40:19.000
and the effect on Ford
was astonishing.

40:20.760 --> 40:26.120
In 1994, they sold
127,000 Mondeos in Britain.

40:26.160 --> 40:30.160
In 2017,
that was down to 12,000.

40:32.160 --> 40:36.280
And 85% of those
12,000 were fleet sales,

40:36.320 --> 40:38.320
hire car companies
and the police.

40:38.360 --> 40:41.560
And that means only
1900 Mondeos

40:41.600 --> 40:43.520
were sold to private buyers.

40:43.560 --> 40:47.200
-Yeah, people that actually
went and bought one.
-Yeah, 1900.

40:47.280 --> 40:49.040
And, if you think about it,

40:49.080 --> 40:51.280
Ford has 500 dealers
in Britain, yeah?

40:51.320 --> 40:54.600
-Yeah.
-Each of those will have
taken two Mondeos a year?

40:54.640 --> 40:57.400
Oh, God, yeah,
as demonstrators.
Yes, they would have done.

40:57.440 --> 40:59.920
-So really, we are...
-900, you're talking about.

40:59.960 --> 41:03.040
900 people actually said,
"I'll buy one of those
with my money."

41:03.080 --> 41:06.120
Yeah, 900 people.

41:06.160 --> 41:10.080
When they used to sell
127,000 of them a year.

41:10.120 --> 41:12.200
-That's an astonishing fact.
-I know.

41:16.480 --> 41:21.160
In America, things are so bad
the Mondeo will be pulled
from the showrooms this year.

41:32.440 --> 41:35.160
And it's predicted
that soon after that,

41:35.200 --> 41:37.560
it'll go from the rest
of the world as well.

41:40.640 --> 41:42.600
And when that happens,

41:42.640 --> 41:45.960
Britain will have lost
much more than just a car.

41:47.960 --> 41:51.160
The Mondeo was never fancy
or spectacular,

41:51.160 --> 41:55.000
it never won Le Mans, it was
never awarded a Nobel Prize,

41:55.040 --> 41:56.960
it didn't write
The Grapes Of Wrath.

41:58.040 --> 41:59.680
It was just your mate,

41:59.760 --> 42:03.040
someone you enjoyed
going to the pub with.

42:07.520 --> 42:08.960
And here's the thing.

42:09.000 --> 42:12.400
When someone fancy
or spectacular like, say,

42:12.440 --> 42:16.360
Mick Jagger dies,
it'll be sad.

42:16.400 --> 42:20.880
But when your mate dies,
that is heart-breaking.

42:20.920 --> 42:22.840
(FUNEREAL MUSIC)

42:26.480 --> 42:29.440
So, to give this car
the send-off it deserves...

42:32.040 --> 42:34.080
...we've booked
Lincoln Cathedral.

42:41.760 --> 42:44.920
And invited some
like-minded souls

42:44.960 --> 42:47.040
to mark the moment
of its passing.

42:53.960 --> 42:56.760
This'll be a funeral
for a friend.

43:05.400 --> 43:07.480
A few people
have turned up already.

43:07.520 --> 43:09.440
Look at that.

43:16.080 --> 43:19.160
JEREMY: Big, isn't it?
RICHARD: Very.

43:19.160 --> 43:22.840
Tallest building in the world
for 250 years, this.

43:22.880 --> 43:26.040
How many people do you think
are gonna turn up?

43:26.080 --> 43:28.080
Well, it is
a Tuesday afternoon.

43:28.120 --> 43:30.120
Well, we might get 50.

43:30.160 --> 43:32.280
No, I think it could be 100.

43:32.320 --> 43:35.600
-100 would be nice,
wouldn't it?
-Yeah.

43:35.640 --> 43:38.080
JEREMY: In fact, it was
rather more than 100.

43:51.480 --> 43:53.080
So many people came,

43:53.120 --> 43:56.360
that the traffic in Lincoln
ground to a halt.

43:56.400 --> 43:58.120
(HORN BLARES)

43:59.520 --> 44:02.360
(HORNS BLARING)

44:02.400 --> 44:05.640
And we had to begin
the service before
they'd all arrived.

